article.headline: Minnesota 63, North Dakota State 49
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Lawrence McKenzie tossed and turned all night after Minnesota lost to Division-II Winona State last week, and his paltry shooting that night was still on his mind when the Gophers opened the regular season Monday against North Dakota State. McKenzie should sleep much better after this one. The transfer from Oklahoma had 20 points and 10 rebounds and Spencer Tollackson scored all 12 of his points in the second half to lift Minnesota to a 63-49 victory over the Bison. "That night, I couldn't even sleep after that game," McKenzie said of the 69-64 exhibition loss to the Warriors, in which he made just 4 of 16 shots from the field. "There was a chip on our shoulder." Dan Coleman added 13 points for the Gophers (1-0), who got off to a very sluggish start before pulling away in the second half. Andre Smith was outstanding for the Bison (1-1) with 17 points, a career-high 17 rebounds, four blocks and three steals. "He might have been the best player on the floor tonight," Tollackson said. But while the Bison thoroughly outplayed the Gophers football team in a 10-9 loss at the Metrodome in October, NDSU fell flat in this one. Smith was the only Bison player who looked like he truly belonged on the floor, even against a decidedly mediocre Gophers team with no seniors. Williams Arena used to be one of the loudest, most difficult places to play in the country. But the Gophers' struggles under embattled coach Dan Monson over the last eight seasons have severely muted the crowd and alienated the once-fervent fan base. No doubt in part because of the loss to Winona State, there were thousands of empty seats for the Gophers' season-opener, once one of the most anticipated events on campus. "Obviously the Winona loss really put them in the cross hairs," NDSU coach Tim Miles said. "If something like that doesn't put a fire under your butt I don't know what will." Said Tollackson: "Everybody kind of had a pit in their stomach and a bitter taste in their mouth." Those who stayed at home didn't miss much in the first half. Most of the period looked like it belonged in an intramural gymnasium rather than a Division I arena. In the first 10 minutes, the Gophers shot 17.6 percent while the Bison shot 16.7 percent. The Bison looked nervous for most of the game. They missed 10 of their first 12 shots and had eight turnovers in the first 10 minutes. "It's our fifth straight day on the road," Miles said of the Bison, who opened with a win at Idaho. "I think our kids are tired of being on the road." Still, 7:30 into the game, North Dakota State led 5-4. McKenzie finally put together a spurt, hitting two 3-pointers and a fast break layup in less than a minute to give the Gophers a 14-5 lead. Yet with his team seemingly on the cusp of breaking the game open, Monson yanked McKenzie 30 seconds later, and North Dakota State outscored Minnesota 9-2 over the next 2:45. The Bison trailed by five at halftime, but had no answer for Tollackson's size and McKenzie's quickness in the second half. "I think this whole preseason's going to be a process," Monson said. "If we have to lose to Winona State, if that helps us beat North Dakota State, then so be it." Minnesota shot 54 percent in the second half, with many of its buckets coming on layups by Tollackson underneath. North Dakota State shot just 29 percent for the game, with Ben Woodside and Brett Winkelman combining to shoot 5-for-21. "We couldn't finish on the offensive end," Woodside said. "We stopped them for a while, but you have to score on the other end and we didn't do that very well."
